So I want to be able to
work half days on Fridays

00:32:58.170 --> 00:33:00.320
so I can take this
rock climbing class.

00:33:00.320 --> 00:33:02.074
Let's try to make that happen.

00:33:02.074 --> 00:33:04.490
So I want to make sure that
you have this sense of growth.

00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:06.960
When you have a sense of
growth, then what happens?

00:33:06.960 --> 00:33:08.609
You're satisfied.

00:33:08.609 --> 00:33:10.150
You feel like this
is a place for me.

00:33:10.150 --> 00:33:11.983
This is a place I can
spend my whole career.

00:33:11.983 --> 00:33:15.220
It's valuable to me.

00:33:15.220 --> 00:33:16.650
Last component is natural.

00:33:16.650 --> 00:33:19.760
So as I said earlier, sometimes,
particularly as supervisors,

00:33:19.760 --> 00:33:22.240
we think we have
to know everything.

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:25.820
And it's really beautiful
to be imperfect.

00:33:25.820 --> 00:33:28.730
In fact, one of the
key ways to initiate

00:33:28.730 --> 00:33:31.220
the release of oxytocin
is just ask for help.

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:33.850
And you ask for help
when you need help.

00:33:33.850 --> 00:33:36.120
So there's a finding in
psychology called the Pratfall

00:33:36.120 --> 00:33:37.290
effect.

00:33:37.290 --> 00:33:40.970
So if you stumble, people are
much more willing to help you.

00:33:40.970 --> 00:33:42.690
You're seen as
much more likable.

00:33:42.690 --> 00:33:47.440
So a classic example of this was
right after the Cuban Missile

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:50.510
Crisis in the 1960s.

00:33:50.510 --> 00:33:52.830
All went south quickly.

00:33:52.830 --> 00:33:55.710
And so Kennedy goes
on TV and he says,

00:33:55.710 --> 00:33:57.650
I approved this
invasion of Cuba.

00:33:57.650 --> 00:33:59.480
I thought it was a good thing.

00:33:59.480 --> 00:34:01.490
Soviets are involved,
blah, blah, blah.

00:34:01.490 --> 00:34:02.740
We blew it.

00:34:02.740 --> 00:34:03.240
I blew it.

00:34:03.240 --> 00:34:04.380
I'm the President.

00:34:04.380 --> 00:34:06.710
The military advisers
gave me bad advice.

00:34:06.710 --> 00:34:08.404
And I want to be a
better president.

00:34:08.404 --> 00:34:10.469
So I'm going to try to
get better at this job.

00:34:10.469 --> 00:34:12.080
I've only been doing
this for a year.

00:34:12.080 --> 00:34:13.080
And I want your support.

00:34:13.080 --> 00:34:16.190
And I want to be the best
leader for the United States.

00:34:16.190 --> 00:34:19.030
His approval ratings went
up after the Bay of Pigs

00:34:19.030 --> 00:34:20.820
because he owned the mistake.

00:34:20.820 --> 00:34:24.190
Now, it's important that
you're seen as competent.

00:34:24.190 --> 00:34:26.659
If you're stumbling and
you're seen as incompetent,

00:34:26.659 --> 00:34:28.050
then it just hurts you.

00:34:28.050 --> 00:34:29.550
But as long as
you're competent, you

00:34:29.550 --> 00:34:34.000
can say, look, it didn't work
for-- this one didn't work out.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:36.239
Wasn't so good.

00:34:36.239 --> 00:34:36.739
So what?

00:34:36.739 --> 00:34:38.710
We'll move on.

00:34:38.710 --> 00:34:39.739
I'm OK with that.

00:34:39.739 --> 00:34:40.935
So live up to your mistakes.

00:34:40.935 --> 00:34:41.889
Own your mistakes.

00:34:41.889 --> 00:34:43.230
Allow yourself to be vulnerable.

00:34:43.230 --> 00:34:45.659
Southwest Airlines, which
we all fly in California,

00:34:45.659 --> 00:34:46.730
see that a lot.

00:34:46.730 --> 00:34:49.500
You see funny flight attendants.

00:34:49.500 --> 00:34:52.460
Herb Kelleher, who's the
founder and CEO for many years

00:34:52.460 --> 00:34:55.449
would toss the luggage with
the luggage handler people,

00:34:55.449 --> 00:34:56.949
would hand out
drinks on the planes,

00:34:56.949 --> 00:34:59.290
wear a funny monkey
suit to work one day.

00:34:59.290 --> 00:35:01.870
It's about really just
being himself, having fun.

00:35:01.870 --> 00:35:02.710
That's OK.

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:03.710
And it's very appealing.

00:35:03.710 --> 00:35:06.360
And people loved him.

00:35:06.360 --> 00:35:08.440
So if we take all
of those factors,

00:35:08.440 --> 00:35:10.850
which again are not
statistically independent.

00:35:10.850 --> 00:35:12.660
Regress them on
organizational trust,

00:35:12.660 --> 00:35:15.010
we explain 100% of the
variation in trust.

00:35:15.010 --> 00:35:17.290
So there are no other classes
of measurement factors

00:35:17.290 --> 00:35:19.130
we need to worry about.

00:35:19.130 --> 00:35:22.590
So what we're trying to do
is design this environment,

00:35:22.590 --> 00:35:25.121
measure and
intervene in a series

00:35:25.121 --> 00:35:26.620
of controlled
experiments-- and I'll

00:35:26.620 --> 00:35:28.220
talk about that
in just a second--

00:35:28.220 --> 00:35:30.031
so that you are so engaged.

00:35:30.031 --> 00:35:32.030
And you're engaged not
only internally, but also

00:35:32.030 --> 00:35:33.590
externally.

00:35:33.590 --> 00:35:37.810
If I love what I do at
Google, I'm excited about it,

00:35:37.810 --> 00:35:41.280
and I see an end user, am
I like, yeah, whatever.

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:42.235
I work at Google.

00:35:42.235 --> 00:35:43.310
They're like, yeah.

00:35:43.310 --> 00:35:45.530
It's a really cool
place to work.

00:35:45.530 --> 00:35:46.411
It's challenging.

00:35:46.411 --> 00:35:46.910
It's hard.

00:35:46.910 --> 00:35:49.150
There's super crazy
brilliant people.

00:35:49.150 --> 00:35:53.360
And we're trying to solve big
honking problems every day.

00:35:53.360 --> 00:35:55.870
That's super engaging.

00:35:55.870 --> 00:35:57.360
As opposed to, eh, whatever.

00:35:57.360 --> 00:35:58.100
They pay me.

00:35:58.100 --> 00:35:58.830
I show up.

00:35:58.830 --> 00:35:59.930
I don't want that guy.

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:02.620
So I like what I call
