00:42:10.760 --> 00:42:12.359
Kind of get continuous
improvement.

00:42:12.359 --> 00:42:14.150
Little management
experiments all the time.

00:42:14.150 --> 00:42:16.447
And I know you guys do
this all the time anyway.

00:42:16.447 --> 00:42:18.530
But I'm trying to give you
a theoretical structure

00:42:18.530 --> 00:42:19.770
underneath that.

00:42:19.770 --> 00:42:22.520
It's really about
building a culture

00:42:22.520 --> 00:42:25.770
in which social
relationships are paramount.

00:42:25.770 --> 00:42:27.240
They're really,
really efficient.

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:31.970
So I think of trust
as a social lubricant.

00:42:31.970 --> 00:42:33.470
When trust is high,
it's easy to get

00:42:33.470 --> 00:42:35.610
things done because the
frictions are lower.

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:37.559
And it includes getting
things done at work.

00:42:37.559 --> 00:42:39.100
It's just easier
when I trust people.

00:42:39.100 --> 00:42:43.060
So I want to thoughtfully
design a culture for high trust

00:42:43.060 --> 00:42:45.970
because I want to reduce
those frictions at work.

00:42:45.970 --> 00:42:47.460
So here's an example.

00:42:47.460 --> 00:42:51.770
We worked with a large-ish
insurance company,

00:42:51.770 --> 00:42:53.480
whose name you would know.

00:42:53.480 --> 00:42:55.610
And they had retention problems.

00:42:55.610 --> 00:42:59.430
And their retention problems
were in a particular division.

00:42:59.430 --> 00:43:00.350
And so we said, OK.

00:43:00.350 --> 00:43:01.730
Let's work on that division.

00:43:01.730 --> 00:43:04.420
So your problem
is high turnover.

00:43:04.420 --> 00:43:06.140
And so when we did
the O Factor survey,

00:43:06.140 --> 00:43:09.040
