00:44:39.445 --> 00:44:41.240
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about oxytocin.

00:44:41.240 --> 00:44:42.114
PAUL ZAK: Yes, ma'am.

00:44:42.114 --> 00:44:45.580
AUDIENCE: I'm wondering how
much the baseline levels differ

00:44:45.580 --> 00:44:48.210
between individuals generally,
and if they are drastically

00:44:48.210 --> 00:44:51.160
lower in people who
are, like, psychopaths

00:44:51.160 --> 00:44:54.789
or maybe suffer from
forms of autism or--

00:44:54.789 --> 00:44:55.830
PAUL ZAK: Great question.

00:44:55.830 --> 00:44:58.875
And so the back story on
this, what started out

00:44:58.875 --> 00:45:01.550
as basic science research did
spawn a lot of clinical trials

00:45:01.550 --> 00:45:04.650
for things like autism,
schizophrenia, social anxiety,

00:45:04.650 --> 00:45:06.110
depression.

00:45:06.110 --> 00:45:09.820
We've work with
psychopaths in prisons.

00:45:09.820 --> 00:45:14.520
So oxytocin, like many
other chemicals in the body,

00:45:14.520 --> 00:45:16.010
is re-used.

00:45:16.010 --> 00:45:18.760
So it functions
outside the brain

00:45:18.760 --> 00:45:21.970
to facilitate uterine
contractions during birth,

00:45:21.970 --> 00:45:23.864
milk letdown for breastfeeding.

00:45:23.864 --> 00:45:25.530
But in the brain, it
functions much more

00:45:25.530 --> 00:45:28.720
like a neurotransmitter,
that is, acute responses.

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:34.550
And so the secret on why it
really hadn't been studied

00:45:34.550 --> 00:45:36.740
outside of reproduction is
no one figured out a way

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:39.350
to actually measure that acute
brain response, and we did.

00:45:39.350 --> 00:45:41.020
And once we had this tool,
then you can go to town

00:45:41.020 --> 00:45:42.770
and ask a lot of
questions with that tool.

00:45:42.770 --> 00:45:44.569
And this was based
on animal research.

00:45:44.569 --> 00:45:47.110
So I took the animal research,
turned it into human research,

00:45:47.110 --> 00:45:48.450
which is not always trivial.

00:45:48.450 --> 00:45:50.530
But once we had that, it worked.

00:45:50.530 --> 00:45:54.130
So what we found is that
everybody makes oxytocin,

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:56.840
they just don't always
make it at the right times.

00:45:56.840 --> 00:46:00.800
So if you're having a really
bad day, high levels of stress,

00:46:00.800 --> 00:46:02.540
you inhibit oxytocin release.

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:04.510
If you had a very
adverse childhood,

00:46:04.510 --> 00:46:07.530
abuse neglect history,
then the brain regions that

00:46:07.530 --> 00:46:10.900
should have many oxytocin
receptors atrophy,

00:46:10.900 --> 00:46:14.130
and then you don't get
this feel good effect

00:46:14.130 --> 00:46:18.470
that we get when we interact
with people in a nice way.

00:46:18.470 --> 00:46:22.280
In the psychopathic study,
this is research coming out

00:46:22.280 --> 00:46:25.481
soon in a journal, we found that
all those guys make oxytocin.

00:46:25.481 --> 00:46:26.730
So it's not the chronic level.

00:46:26.730 --> 00:46:28.340
It's this acute response.

00:46:28.340 --> 00:46:29.844
And that's the trick.

00:46:29.844 --> 00:46:32.010
They don't get the acute
response in the right away.

00:46:32.010 --> 00:46:34.260
And, in fact, they
make lots of oxytocin

00:46:34.260 --> 00:46:36.380
because their receptors
are dysfunctional.

00:46:36.380 --> 00:46:38.470
And what do they lack primarily?

00:46:38.470 --> 00:46:40.090
Psychopaths lack empathy.

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:42.730
And that's exactly what
oxytocin increases most.

00:46:42.730 --> 00:46:48.700
So oxytocin is an
innate moral compass.

00:46:48.700 --> 00:46:51.450
I'm getting feedback when I
interact with the humans based

00:46:51.450 --> 00:46:54.900
on their body language,
the way they treat me,

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:58.204
their expressions, on whether
my behavior was appropriate.

00:46:58.204 --> 00:46:59.620
And once you've
been on the planet

00:46:59.620 --> 00:47:01.120
for more than about
20 years, you've

00:47:01.120 --> 00:47:04.760
figured out that I could get
Eric to help me with my project

00:47:04.760 --> 00:47:06.990
by beating the crap
out of him, or I

00:47:06.990 --> 00:47:08.220
could treat him really nice.

00:47:08.220 --> 00:47:09.532
Eric, you're super smart, man.

00:47:09.532 --> 00:47:10.240
Do you have time?

00:47:10.240 --> 00:47:12.573
Do you have like half an hour
you can help me with this?

00:47:12.573 --> 00:47:14.290
That's a much better
approach, right?

00:47:14.290 --> 00:47:19.100
So anyway, it doesn't take
a genius to figure that out.

00:47:19.100 --> 00:47:23.290
But the hard part
is taking this quote

00:47:23.290 --> 00:47:28.140
"reproductive" hormone as
one of my colleagues said,

00:47:28.140 --> 00:47:31.050
this female hormone, and
showing that we all release it.

00:47:31.050 --> 00:47:32.590
And in the right
circumstances, it

00:47:32.590 --> 00:47:35.320
guides us to the
appropriate social behavior.

00:47:35.320 --> 00:47:36.980
So yeah, great science question.

00:47:36.980 --> 00:47:37.646
Thank you.

